# <type>(<scope>): <subject>
#
# <body>
# 
# Detailed explanation of the change, why it was made, and any relevant context.
#
# <footer>
# 
# BREAKING CHANGE: Description of the breaking change, if applicable.
#
# type: feat, fix, docs, style, refactor, test, chore
# scope: optional (e.g., renderer, ui, config)
# subject: Use the imperative mood (e.g., "add", "fix", "update")
# 
# Examples:
# 
# feat(panel): add resizable panel functionality
# fix(webview): resolve issue with webview not loading
# docs(README): update installation instructions
#
# Instructions:
#
# 1. Use the Commit Template
# You have already created a commit template in .gitmessage. This helps you maintain the structure for your commits.
#
# 2. Write the Commit Message
# When you make a commit, open the editor to write the message. Hereâ€™s how to do it:
#
# Stage Changes:
# git add .
#
# Execute Commit:
# git commit
#
# Editor Opens:
# Your template will be displayed. Fill it out by adding the relevant information. For example:
# feat(ui): add dark mode toggle
# Implement a toggle for dark mode in the UI to enhance user experience.
# BREAKING CHANGE: The default theme is now dark.
#
# 3. Commit Types
# Here are the types you can use:
#
# feat: for new features
# fix: for bug fixes
# docs: for documentation changes
# style: for formatting changes that do not affect logic (e.g., whitespace, formatting)
# refactor: for code changes that do not add new features or fix bugs
# test: for adding or modifying tests
# chore: for changes that do not affect the code (e.g., build processes)
#
# 4. Example Commits
# Here are some examples of how to formulate your commits:
#
# Adding a New Feature:
# feat(panel): add resizable panel functionality
#
# Bug Fix:
# fix(webview): resolve issue with webview not loading
#
# Updating Documentation:
# docs(README): update installation instructions
#
# 5. Execute the Commit
# After you have filled out the message, save and close the editor. Your commit will then be created with the specified message.
#
# 6. Update the CHANGELOG
# After the commit, you can update the CHANGELOG with the following command:
# npm run changelog